{most common position in amateur games and how to win it} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bc4 Bc5 {typical italian game} 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 {most common position, if
recently started playing/ most logical development} 6. Bg5 {Be3 or Na4 are
actually good moves, but Bg5 is most popular}  (6. h3 {to stop Bg4 knight pin} 
6... h6 7. Be3 {good continuation}  (7. O-O g5 {4th most popular move with over
60% win rate} 8. Nh2 {strongest move but hard to find without preparation, can
continue with Be6, Qd7, O-O-O}  (8. Be3 g4 {forces white to exchange} 9. hxg4
Bxg4 10. Bxc5 dxc5 11. Nd5 {most popular move} 11... Nd4 {simple pin wins as
white pawns will be ruined and king is exposed} 12. c3 Nxf3+ 13. gxf3 Bh3 {rook
joins in g8 square} 14. Re1 Nxd5 {and deliever mate on g2} ) ) 7... Bb6 {does
not allow exchange with opponent terms} )  (6. O-O Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 {black don't
rush to castle} 8. Be3 {best move again}  (8. g4 Nxg4 {very interesting
sacrifice} 9. hxg4 Bxg4 {Qf6 or Nd4 to increase pressure on pin} 10. Be3 {only
correct move} 10... Qf6 11. Nd5 Qg6 {brings queen to attack} 12. Nxc7+
{basically admitting defeat, as taking rook allows checkmate}  (12. Nh4 Qh5) ) 
(8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nd4 {bring knight into attack to ruin opponent
pawn structure} 11. a3 (11. Nd5 {most popular move essentially loses the game} 
11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 c6 {drives bishop away from d5 to defend b7} 13. Bc4 Qf6
{white can't get rid of the pressure} 14. c3 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 Bxf3 16. Qd2 h5
{push outside pawnh4,g4,Rg1 and white falls back} ) 11... Qd7) ) 6... h6 {never
support opponent with symmetric Bg4} 7. Bxf6 {nothing to worry about, simple
development}  (7. Bh4 {usually white don't want to exchange already developed
pieces} 7... g5 {not yet castled, so don't need to be afraid; after castling
must look out for knight sacrifices} 8. Bg3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 {and white can't play
g4, knight is pinned and bishop has no prospect there} 10. Qd2 (10. Bh2 Bxf3 (
10... Na5 {to exchange light squared bishop} )  (10... Qe7 11. g4 Bg6 {allows
symmetry} ) 11. Qxf3 Nd4 {equal, but h2 bishop is locked in} ) 10... Bxf3
{ruins opponent pawn structure} 11. gxf3 Nd4) 7... Qxf6 8. Nd5 Qd8 { defends
